HTTP adaptive Streaming
Adaptive HTTP streaming is the preferred method to deliver multimedia content on the internet. It provides multiple representations of the same content in different qualities (i.e., bit-rates and resolutions)
and allows the client to request segments from the available representations in a dynamic, adaptive way depending on its context. The growing number of representations in adaptive HTTP streaming makes encoding of one video segment at different representations a challenging task in terms of encoding time-complexity.

The main goal is:
Smooth Playback
without Buffering or Freezing

It is the core technology behind:
YouTube
Netflix
Twitch
Amazon Prime Video

Basic Idea
Instead of sending only one video quality, the server stores multiple versions:
| Quality | Bitrate  |
| ------- | -------- |
| 240p    | 300 kbps |
| 480p    | 1 Mbps   |
| 720p    | 3 Mbps   |
| 1080p   | 6 Mbps   |
| 4K      | 15 Mbps  |
The client/player dynamically switches quality depending on bandwidth.

Working Principle
Step 1: Video Encoding
The original video is encoded into:
Multiple resolutions
Multiple bitrates

Example:
360p
720p
1080p

using codecs such as:
x264
x265
AOMedia Video 1

Step 2: Video Segmentation
Video is divided into small chunks:
segment1.ts
segment2.ts
segment3.ts

Typical segment duration:
2–10 seconds

Step 3: Manifest File
A playlist/manifest describes:
Available resolutions
Bitrates
Segment locations

Examples:
M3U8 for HLS
MPD for DASH

Step 4: Adaptive Client Playback
The player continuously measures:
Available bandwidth
Buffer level
Playback performance

and selects the most suitable bitrate.

Architecture
Video Source
      ↓
Multi-Bitrate Encoder
      ↓
Segmenter
      ↓
HTTP Server/CDN
      ↓
Adaptive Player
      ↓
Viewer

Major HTTP Adaptive Streaming Protocols
1. HLS (HTTP Live Streaming)
Developed by:
Apple

Uses:
M3U8 playlist
TS/fMP4 segments

Widely supported on:
iPhone
Smart TVs
OTT platforms

2. MPEG-DASH
Standardized by:
MPEG
Uses:
MPD manifest

Codec independent:
AVC
HEVC
AV1
VVC

3. Low-Latency HLS (LL-HLS)
Improved HLS for:
Live sports
Esports
Interactive streaming

Latency:
~2–5 seconds

Adaptive Bitrate (ABR) Algorithms
ABR logic decides quality switching.

Parameters:
Throughput estimation
Buffer occupancy
Packet loss
QoE metrics

Popular ABR methods:
Throughput-based
Buffer-based
Hybrid ABR
AI/ML-based ABR

Example of Adaptive Switching
Suppose:
User starts at 1080p
Internet speed drops

Player automatically switches:
1080p → 720p → 480p
without stopping playback.
When bandwidth improves:
Quality increases again.

Advantages
1. Reduced Buffering
Main advantage.
2. Better User Experience
Continuous playback.
3. Scalability
Uses normal HTTP servers and CDNs.
4. Firewall Friendly
Works over standard HTTP/HTTPS.
5. Device Compatibility
Works on:
Mobile
TV
Browser
Gaming console

Challenges
1. Latency
Traditional HAS introduces delay:
10–30 seconds
Problematic for:
Esports
Video conferencing
2. Quality Oscillation
Frequent bitrate switching may degrade QoE.
3. Bandwidth Estimation Errors
Incorrect prediction can cause buffering.

